Exactly 20 yrs ago, i took a leap of faith in a small town called Lexington, Kentucky & dropped out of community college & quit my watchman / security job to become a full time DJ & never looked back (maybe coz i never had a Plan B - this had to work).

It’s been an amazing two decades filled with extreme highs & lows but the journey has been worth every step. I’ve met some amazing people along the way & learnt some valuable lessons that have become life principles - which i share from time to time.

My biggest flex is I’ve remained true to myself & never stopped believing in me even when the odds have been against me. Most importantly, I’ve made every industry & community that I entered better in some way than i found it, all while serving The People.

It’s taken me years to realize the goal isn’t to win the game before the clock runs out, but to keep the clock running & stay in the game for as long as it takes.

So here’s to 20 more years of service, leadership, impact & most importantly good times! 

Let’s Fking Goooo

“The genius thing we did is we never gave up” - Hov.

Over the past 2 weeks Atlanta has lost two of the most important individuals to the nightlife scene & to my story. In the 17 yrs i’ve lived in the city, i got the privilege to see excellence by black brothers building their empires.

When i decided to launch @pxppresents in 2014 it was #MichaelGidewon who took a chance on me & allowed us to execute it monthly at his club Reign. He’d give sound advice & at one point helped front production costs coz we couldn’t afford it coz he wanted us to win. What he & his brother @agentertainement have done for the city for 3 decades will never be duplicated.

A year later i decided to take @pxppresents outdoors to launch it as a festival. I had the idea, the park, the line up except one thing… the funding. Everyone i asked said No, then @whatuptory & his brother #TerrenceClark from @suiteloungeatl stepped in, took a chance on me & the rest is history. Their impact in the city will continue to live forever.

Without these individuals, my dream may have never come true so I’m forever indebted to these brothers & heart broken by the losses. 

My sincere condolences to out to both families. May peace, strength, healing, love & joy forever be theirs & may they never lack for generations to come.

#RestInPeace 🙏🏾

For the first time I got to truly understand why so many people also refer to her as mom & her secret to a long happy life :

Love unconditionally 
Laugh uncontrollably 
Live unforgettably 

I’m beyond grateful for these precious moments and to experience her & yes i tell her this everyday, for you can’t be around love & not be influenced by it.

Happy Mother’s Day to all mothers, whether here or gone, whether with a child or have ever lost one 🙏🏾❤️

The difficulty of being a dope DJ & organize events globally is one only those who’ve done can truly appreciate. Reason being it’s practically been nonexistent in the black community so it’s a figure-it-out-as-you-go kind of thing all while still playing gigs, touring, putting out music, mixes & remixes. For that, there’s VERY few DJs in this industry I admire & respect for the vision & ability to create their own event movement, that’s not artist dependent. @djmoma is a prime example of this w/ his @everydayppl brand that’s consistently delivered & grown for 10+ years. This week i got to experience & witness the amazing community he’s built in NYC & incredible team he works with & frankly I’m inspired. If he or his event is ever in your city, make sure you go check it out. From one DJ to another - Salute🫡 

#StayFocused

Last night we got to witness a theatrical masterpiece by @kendricklamar at @glblctzn in Rwanda. The attention to detail, production, showmanship & energy was one of the best I’ve ever witnessed. Each song was like a scene of a play, powerful & potent. He also incorporated local talent (kids & dancers) in some of the songs which was dope. 

What i loved the most is the ability to communicate the message of a song using symbolism without ritualism, something some of our popping African artists can learn from. Art is subjective but there’s a million ways to communicate a message not always dark energies.

Beyond that, the event was extremely well organized & the venue was A++. I’ve been telling people for a decade Rwanda has a culture of Excellence that will take Africa to the next level & last night lots of people who hadn’t seen it before got to witness. Cant wait to see what else they have in store for the world, a big thanks to @visitrwanda_now  @rdbrwanda for the tix & incredible hospitality.

Every industry has politics & a lot of BS that happens behind the scenes that people don’t know about. The longer you stay in the business the more you get to see people’s true colors. Yes even in the DJ industry, some of your favorites are weird & phony & when you’re the opposite it can put you off & discourage you. Eventually you learn to move accordingly coz you know who you are & know who they’re not, when you do, you can speak truth freely coz you built your career outside of the circle they tried so hard to keep you out of & now can’t do anything about. I’m not saying everything Katt said in this interview is gospel coz I wasn’t there, but I can relate having experienced similar things in mine, though it never stopped me from elevating, eventually truth always comes out. 

#StayFocused

I met Wes (@diplo) 10 yrs ago when i took @timayatimaya to Trinidad for the first time to meet / perform w/ @machelmontano during carnival. 

While backstage @walshyfire introduced us since i’d been booking Walsh for my events in ATL since 2010.  A few months later I told them we should do a @majorlazer mixtape for African music since no one was pushing that on the mainstream (non-African spaces) & streaming wasn’t a thing yet and #AfricaIsTheFuture was born (more on that later)

Over the years we stayed connected & in 2018 when Diplo got his channel on @siriusxm he asked me if i wanted to do an African mix show & ofcourse i was down & made some noise with that.

That same year i landed my Las Vegas residency on the strip, it just so happened that was the same year another African DJ landed his, namely @realblackcoffee though his was far bigger lol. I used to finish my set & head to see @diplo do his while sharing new music for him to break to a predominantly white audience.

Fast forward to today, we shot the video for my artist @sofiyanzau big hit #Mwaki Major Lazer remix here in Nairobi. Showing the urban culture of Matatu which is where i fell in love with DJing (yes i was a tout too). 

Wes has always been a real one & genuinely supportive of the culture by collaborating & magnifying whatever is brewing, before it’s popular & convenient.

Grateful of such allies & relationships in the ever continuing battle of pushing African music.

Life is full circle.

#StayFocused
